  "prompt": "What colleges can I get into with a 4.8 weighted GPA and 2130 SAT score?",
  "response": "A weighted GPA of 4.8 and an SAT score of 2130 (out of 2400) are strong academic credentials that position you as a competitive applicant for many colleges and universities. However, the specific schools you can target will depend on other factors like your extracurricular activities, essays, letters of recommendation, and the rigor of your high school coursework. Here\u2019s a breakdown of potential colleges you might consider:\n\n### **Reach Schools (Highly Competitive)**\nThese schools are highly selective, but your GPA and SAT score make you a competitive applicant:\n- **Ivy League Schools** (e.g., Harvard, Yale, Princeton, Columbia, etc.)  \n  While these schools are reaches for nearly everyone, your profile is strong enough to warrant applying.\n- **Stanford University**\n- **Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)**\n- **University of Chicago**\n- **California Institute of Technology (Caltech)**\n\n### **Target Schools (Good Fit)**\nThese schools are excellent matches for your academic profile:\n- **University of California (UC) System** (e.g., UC Berkeley, UCLA, UC San Diego)  \n  The UC system uses its own GPA calculation (called the UC GPA), but your weighted GPA of 4.8 is impressive.\n- **University of Michigan**\n- **University of Virginia**\n- **University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill**\n- **New York University (NYU)**\n- **Boston University**\n- **University of Southern California (USC)**\n\n### **Safety Schools (Likely to Get In)**\nThese schools are likely to admit you based on your GPA and SAT score:\n- **Penn State University**\n- **University of Florida**\n- **University of Texas at Austin** (note: Texas has its own GPA scale, but your profile is strong)\n- **University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign**\n- **University of Washington**\n- **University of Georgia**\n\n### **Additional Considerations**\n1. **Test-Optional Schools**: Many schools have adopted test-optional policies, so if you feel your SAT score doesn\u2019t fully reflect your potential, consider applying to schools that don\u2019t require SAT scores.\n2. **STEM vs. Liberal Arts**: If you\u2019re focused on STEM fields, your SAT math score will be particularly important. For liberal arts, your verbal and writing scores matter more.\n3. **Holistic Admissions**: Many schools consider essays, extracurriculars, and recommendations heavily. Make sure these aspects of your application are strong.\n\n### **Next Steps**\n- Research schools that align with your interests, location preferences, and career goals.\n- Visit campuses (if possible) or attend virtual tours to get a feel for each school.\n- Work on crafting compelling essays and gathering strong letters of recommendation.\n\nYour academic profile is impressive, so aim high while balancing your list with reaches, targets, and safeties. Good luck!",
